Technological determinism is a concept that covers a wide range of ideas in practice, ranging from technological impetus or technological imperative to a firm belief that human destiny is guided by the logic of science and its legality in technology.
The majority of the interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: that technology itself follows a path that is largely culturally or politically influenced, and that technology itself has an impact on society that is more internal than socially conditioned.
For example, it can be said that the development of road development of motor vehicles will certainly lead to the existence of roads.
However, the domestic road network is not economically feasible for only a few cars, which is why new production methods are being sought to reduce the cost of owning a car.
Mass ownership of cars also leads to a higher number of accidents on the road, which in turn leads to the invention of new techniques for repairing damaged bodies in healthcare.
